{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505051"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2399"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2399"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.04,0.22,0.57,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111999"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2399"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94064"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"11059"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1678"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1692"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45873"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111999"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old, G1P1, woman presents to her General Practice with irregular menstrual cycles. She reports that her menstrual periods are becoming progressively irregular throughout the past year. Since puberty, her menstrual cycle was regular, bleeding for 5 days out of every 28. Over the past year, her menstrual cycles have lengthened 35 \u2013 45-day cycles with lighter bleeds. She states that she is becoming increasingly anxious and has frequent mood swings, feels flushed and wakes at night with night sweats. She also reports 3 kg of weight loss and is concerned that it could be a malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is sexually active with her long-term partner who has had a vasectomy five years ago. She denies any other sexual partners.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. She has a BMI of 25 kg/m\u00b2. Her vital signs are normal, and the remainder of her physical examination, including the abdominal and pelvic examination, is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in the investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum b-HCG test","Endometrial biopsy","Transvaginal ultrasound","Thyroid function tests","Depression and Anxiety Stress Scale (DASS-21)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis 50-year-old woman has symptoms of irregular menstrual cycles, hot flushes, sleep disturbances, mood swings and night sweats. Her age group and clinical features make the diagnosis of perimenopause likely. Perimenopause is a clinical diagnosis however, investigations should be undertaken to exclude conditions that may exacerbate perimenopausal symptoms such as hyperthyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeasuring \u003Cstrong\u003ETSH level \u003C/strong\u003Eallows clinicians to rule out hyperthyroidism that may present with similar symptoms like irregular cycles, mood swings, hot flushes, weight loss and sleep disturbances. Hyperthyroidism can be easily managed and therefore, this should be ruled out before any formal diagnosis of perimenopause is made.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPregnancy should always be considered in sexually active women of reproductive age. However, pregnancy is less likely with her partner\u2019s vasectomy and that her symptoms have been present for about one year. Whilst a pregnancy test might be considered, priority should be given to excluding hyperthyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndometrial biopsy is necessary to rule out endometrial cancer and abnormal uterine bleeding. However, this usually presents with heavier, prolonged frequent menstrual bleeding rather than longer cycles with lighter bleeding. From this perspective, a transvaginal ultrasound could be considered if such a diagnosis was likely, but the risk does not fit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDepression and anxiety may cause sleep disturbances, weight changes and mood changes as seen in this patient. However, it does not cause irregular menstrual cycles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyperthyroidism should always be considered when there are symptoms of anxiety, feeling flushed, night sweats and weight loss."],"references":["Burger HG, Hale GE, Dennerstein L, Robertson DM. Cycle and hormone changes during perimenopause: the key role of ovarian function. Menopause 2008; 15:603.","Greendale GA, Derby CA, Maki PM. Perimenopause and cognition. Obstet Gynecol Clin North Am 2011; 38:519."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94064"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2399"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94064"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-23T14:36:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-23T14:37:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2399"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111999"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0